Credit Risk¶

Notebook L01: Data Preprocessing and Feature Engineering for Credit Risk Modeling¶

Introduction¶

Credit risk modeling is a crucial component for financial institutions to effectively manage and mitigate the risk of borrower default on loans, credit cards, or other types of credit products. This risk arises when borrowers are unable to repay the full amount owed, including principal and interest, sometimes making only partial payments. To address this, financial institutions leverage both statistical and machine learning techniques to build robust predictive models that assess creditworthiness, manage exposure, and comply with regulatory standards.

Key Concepts and Formulas¶

In credit risk management, the Internal Ratings-Based (IRB) approach is widely used, with two main variants:

  • Foundation IRB: Where Probability of Default (PD) is internally estimated by the bank, while Loss Given Default (LGD) and Exposure at Default (EAD) values are prescribed by regulators.
  • Advanced IRB: Where PD, LGD, and EAD are all estimated internally by the bank using advanced models.

Key definitions are:

  • Probability of Default (PD): The likelihood that a borrower will default on their loan within a one-year horizon, often modeled using logistic regression. It is expressed as a percentage between 0% and 100%, indicating the borrower's risk level.

  • Loss Given Default (LGD): The proportion of the exposure that is lost if a borrower defaults. It is calculated as $LGD = 1 - \text{Recovery Rate}$ and is commonly modeled using beta regression.

  • Exposure at Default (EAD): The total value the bank is exposed to when a borrower defaults. It estimates the outstanding amount at the time of default and is also modeled with beta or linear regression techniques.

  • Expected Loss (EL): The anticipated average loss due to default, computed as:

$$ \text{EL} = \text{PD} \times \text{LGD} \times \text{EAD} $$

This formula integrates the three core risk components into a single metric used for capital allocation, pricing, and risk management.

Types of Credit Risk Models¶

Credit risk modeling can be divided broadly into two types:

  1. Application Models:

    • Used to decide whether to grant a loan and at what interest rate.
    • Employ risk-based pricing where higher risk leads to higher interest rates.

  2. Behavioral Models:

    • Assess whether to extend additional credit to existing borrowers.
    • Often implemented via scorecards derived from PD models.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset utilized for this project contains over 800,000 consumer loans issued between 2007 and 2015 by Lending Club, a major US peer-to-peer lending platform. The dataset includes both discrete and continuous features that require careful preprocessing through fine and coarse classing, followed by conversion into dummy variables.

For modeling purposes, the data is split into two periods:

  • Historical data (2007–2014): Used to build initial Expected Loss models.
  • Recent data (2015): Used to validate and test model robustness on newer borrower profiles.

This temporal split allows evaluation of model stability and predictive power over time.

Project Goal & Compliance¶

The main objective is to develop an AI-powered credit risk modeling pipeline compliant with Basel II regulatory frameworks, delivering:

  • A practical scorecard derived from PD models for daily credit risk decisions.
  • LGD and EAD models to estimate losses accurately.
  • An integrated Expected Loss calculation pipeline.
  • Model validation metrics, including Population Stability Index (PSI), to monitor model performance on recent data.

Project Structure and Notebooks¶

  • Notebook L01: Preprocessing and feature engineering — preparing data via fine/coarse classing and dummy variable creation.
  • Notebook L02: PD modeling using logistic regression and scorecard development, including cutoff rate calculations.
  • Notebook L03: LGD and EAD modeling using beta and linear regression; computing the Expected Loss metric.
  • Notebook L04: Model validation through Population Stability Index and ongoing performance monitoring.

This project reflects my deep passion for credit risk analytics, combining rigorous statistical methodology with machine learning to build models that are not only predictive but also interpretable and aligned with regulatory expectations. By leveraging large-scale datasets and cutting-edge techniques, this work aims to empower financial institutions with reliable tools for better risk management and strategic decision-making.

Objectives of this Notebook¶

  1. Data Cleaning and Preparation: Address missing values, inconsistencies, and anomalies. Convert date fields into meaningful formats to facilitate time-related feature creation.

  2. Feature Engineering:

    • Transform categorical variables using fine and coarse classing techniques. This involves grouping rare categories, reducing dimensionality, and improving model stability.
    • Generate dummy variables (one-hot encoding) for categorical features to make them machine-learning ready.
    • Create derived features that capture important borrower behaviors and loan characteristics, such as length of credit history and employment duration.

  3. Data Segmentation: Partition the dataset into training (2007–2014) and validation (2015) periods. This temporal split simulates real-world deployment scenarios where models are built on historical data and tested on future, unseen data — a crucial step for regulatory compliance and model robustness.

  4. Preparation for Modeling: Structure the dataset into input matrices with reference categories and intercepts needed for logistic and regression models in subsequent notebooks. This preparation ensures seamless model training and evaluation in the following stages.

Summary¶

  • Comprehensive data cleaning and transformation of raw Lending Club loan data.
  • Intelligent categorical encoding through fine and coarse classing techniques.
  • Strategic dataset split to mimic real-world credit risk assessment timelines.
  • Preparation of clean, model-ready datasets for predictive modeling of PD, LGD, and EAD in subsequent notebooks.

There are 74 columns in our dataset. There are several empty cells. It is neccessary to concentrate on some of the columns and handle the empty cells in the coming sections.

After some trial and errors, we come up with the following columns that are found significant to be kept for the predictive models. Therefore, preprocessing will be applied solely on the following columns:

Attn: The preprocessing part is lengthy and takes some time to overview. However, it is repetitive and not complex.

Discrete Variables

  1. 'grade': assigned loan grade
  2. 'sub_grade': LC assigned loan subgrade taxliens
  3. 'home_ownership': the home ownership status provided by the borrower during registration. Values are: RENT, OWN, MORTGAGE, OTHER.
  4. addr_state: The state provided by the borrower in the loan application
  5. 'verification_status': Indicates if the borrowers' joint income was verified by LC, not verified, or if the income source was verified
  6. 'purpose': A category provided by the borrower for the loan request.
  7. 'initial_list_status': The initial listing status of the loan. Possible values are – W, F

Continuous Variables

  1. 'term': number of payments on the loan. Values are in months and can be either 36 or 60.
  2. 'emp_length': Employment length in years. Possible values are between 0 and 10 where 0 means less than one year and 10 means ten or more years.
  3. 'int_rate': Interest rate on the loan
  4. 'mths_since_earliest_cr_line': date the borrower's earliest reported credit line was opened
  5. 'delinq_2yrs': The number of 30+ days past-due incidences of delinquency in the borrower's credit file for the past 2 years
  6. 'inq_last_6mths': The number of inquiries in past 6 months (excluding auto and mortgage inquiries)
  7. 'open_acc': The number of open credit lines in the borrower's credit file
  8. 'pub_rec' : Number of derogatory public records
  9. 'total_acc': The total number of credit lines currently in the borrower's credit file
  10. 'acc_now_delinq': The number of accounts on which the borrower is now delinquent.
  11. 'total_rev_hi_lim': Total revolving high credit/credit limit
  12. 'annual_inc': The self-reported annual income provided by the borrower during registration.
  13. 'dti': A ratio calculated using the borrower’s total monthly debt payments on the total debt obligations, excluding mortgage and the requested LC loan, divided by the borrower’s self-reported monthly income.
  14. 'mths_since_last_delinq': The number of months since the borrower's last delinquency.
  15. 'mths_since_last_record': The number of months since the last public record.

Please note that the following column is not considered in the example herein but would have improved the prediction scores.

  • 'mths_since_issue_d': Months since most recent issue d

4 Discrete Data Preparation - WoE¶

Let's automate the calculation of WoE and IV

Weight of Evidence- Woe To what extent an independent variable would predict a dependent variable

Positive WOE means Distribution of Goods > Distribution of Bads
Negative WOE means Distribution of Goods < Distribution of Bads
Hint : Log of a number > 1 means positive value. If less than 1, it means negative value.

Two ways to classify groups in WoE calculations

  1. Fine Classing: Create 10 to 20 bins/groups for a continuous independent variable and then calculate WOE and IV of the variable.
  2. Coarse Classing: Combine adjacent categories with similar WOE scores

Information Value (IV)

Information value is a useful technique to select important variables in a predictive model. It represents how much independent information it brings originally to explain dependent value. It helps to rank variables on the basis of their importance. The IV is calculated using the following formula :

IV = ∑ (% of non-events - % of events) * WOE

IV categories

  • Less than 0.02 => Not useful for prediction
  • 0.02 to 0.1 => Weak predictive Power
  • 0.1 to 0.3 => Medium predictive Power
  • 0.3 to 0.5 => Strong predictive Power
  • '>0.5 => Suspicious Predictive Power
